## 4. Enterprise MNC Feature Set

### 4.1 Features No Current Model Offers

#### 🏢 Enterprise Identity & Access Management

```
Saturday Enterprise Console
├── Organization-Level Controls
│   ├── SSO/SAML Integration (Okta, Azure AD, OneLogin)
│   ├── Role-Based Access Control (Admin, Developer, Reviewer, Auditor)
│   ├── Team-Level Model Configuration
│   └── Usage Budgets & Alerts per Team/Project
├── Project-Level Controls
│   ├── Allowed Languages & Frameworks
│   ├── Coding Standards Enforcement
│   ├── Security Policy Selection (SOC2, HIPAA, PCI-DSS, GDPR)
│   └── Custom Banned Patterns (regex-based)
└── Individual Controls
    ├── Personal Coding Style Preferences
    ├── IDE Integration Settings
    └── Notification Preferences
```

#### 🔄 Full CI/CD Native Integration

Unlike Claude and Codex which are bolt-on tools, Saturday integrates **natively** into the development pipeline:

| Integration Point | Capability |
|---|---|
| **Pull Request Review** | Auto-reviews PRs against team standards, security policies, and NFRs |
| **Pre-Commit Hooks** | Real-time code validation before commit |
| **Pipeline Stage** | Runs as a CI/CD stage: generates tests, validates security, checks compliance |
| **Incident Response** | Ingests error logs/alerts → diagnoses → generates fix PRs automatically |
| **Documentation** | Auto-generates and updates API docs, README, architecture decision records |

#### 📊 Enterprise Analytics Dashboard

| Metric | What It Tracks |
|---|---|
| Code Acceptance Rate | % of generated code accepted without modification |
| Security Score | Average security rating of generated code over time |
| Productivity Multiplier | Lines of shipped code per developer per sprint vs baseline |
| Technical Debt Impact | Net effect on codebase maintainability index |
| Cost Per Resolution | Average cost to resolve a ticket using Saturday |

### 4.2 Multi-Language & Multi-Framework Mastery

Saturday targets **Tier 1 support** (production-grade) for the 20 most enterprise-critical language/framework combinations:

| Tier | Languages/Frameworks | Benchmark Target |
|---|---|---|
| **Tier 1** (Production) | Python, TypeScript/JavaScript, Java, C#, Go, Rust, C++, Kotlin, Swift, SQL | >95% HumanEval, >85% SWE-bench |
| **Tier 2** (Strong) | Ruby, PHP, Scala, Dart/Flutter, R, MATLAB, Terraform/HCL, Shell/Bash | >85% HumanEval, >70% SWE-bench |
| **Tier 3** (Capable) | Perl, Lua, Haskell, Elixir, COBOL, Assembly, Solidity, VHDL | >70% HumanEval |

### 4.3 Legacy System Support

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **This is where MNC budgets are spent.** Fortune 500 companies have millions of lines of COBOL, mainframe code, and legacy systems. No current AI model handles this well.

Saturday includes:
- **COBOL ↔ Java migration assistant** (trained on real migration datasets)
- **Mainframe modernization patterns** (JCL, CICS, DB2 → modern cloud)
- **Legacy API wrapper generation** (wrap old systems with modern REST/GraphQL)
- **Database migration support** (Oracle → PostgreSQL, DB2 → modern SQL)

